Here are the most relevant Angular-heavy Tech Lead questions + expected answer points:

 A) Role-fit (5 mins)
1.  Walk me through your last 2–3 years. What were you personally accountable for?  
    Strong answer should include: clear ownership (features/modules/architecture), team size, stakeholders, measurable impact, examples of leadership (reviews, delegation, risk mgmt).
2.  What does “Front-End Architecture” mean in your day-to-day?  
    Expect: decisions on module boundaries, shared libs, state strategy, performance standards, testing strategy, CI gates, upgrade strategy, design system governance.

 B) Angular Architecture (12–27 mins)
3.  How do you structure a large Angular codebase?  
    Expect: domain/feature modules, shared/core separation, lazy-loaded routes, strict linting/TS config, library strategy (Nx/monorepo optional), clear boundaries to avoid circular deps.
4.  When do you introduce NgRx (vs services + RxJS)?  
    Expect: criteria (complex shared state, time-travel/debugging needs, multi-step workflows), avoiding over-engineering, feature-store pattern, selectors, effects, entity, facade pattern.
5.  How do you version/publish shared UI libraries without breaking apps?  
    Expect: semantic versioning, deprecation policy, changelogs, backward-compatible APIs, CI validation matrix, migration guides, “canary” adoption.


 C) Angular Deep Dive (27–42 mins) — must-ask
6.  Explain Angular change detection and how you optimize it.  
    Expect: default vs OnPush, immutability, async pipe, trackBy, avoiding function calls in templates, pushing work out of templates, profiling, zone.js awareness.
7.  RxJS: switchMap vs mergeMap vs concatMap—where do you use each?  
    Expect: cancellation with switchMap (typeaheads, route changes), mergeMap for parallel work, concatMap for sequencing, error handling (catchError), avoiding nested subscriptions, takeUntil teardown.
8.  Reactive forms: how do you handle complex/dynamic forms?  
    Expect: FormBuilder, FormArray, custom validators, async validators, typed forms (if applicable), clean valueChanges handling, patchValue vs setValue, performance considerations.
9.  Interceptors/guards/resolvers—give real examples.  
    Expect: auth header + refresh token flow (interceptor), route auth/roles (guard), prefetch critical data (resolver) with error/empty-state handling.
10. Describe an Angular upgrade you led (e.g., 9 → 12). What broke and how did you de-risk it?  
    Expect: incremental upgrades, Angular update guide, dependency audit, strict TS changes, build pipeline updates, testing gates, rollout plan, fallback.


 D) Testing & Quality (42–52 mins)
11. How do you unit test Observables/services and components (Jasmine/Karma)?  
    Expect: TestBed setup, mocking HttpClient (HttpTestingController), marble testing optional, fakeAsync/tick, stable selectors, testing async pipe flows, avoiding brittle DOM tests.
12. What’s your overall testing strategy (unit/integration/e2e) for Angular apps?  
    Expect: test pyramid, critical user journeys for e2e, contract tests for APIs if possible, CI enforcement, coverage used wisely (not vanity).


 E) Leadership (52–58 mins)
13. How do you run code reviews for Angular/RxJS/NgRx work?  
    Expect: checklist (architecture boundaries, state anti-patterns, memory leaks, template perf, typing), mentoring tone, consistency via lint rules and shared patterns.
14. How do you manage tech debt in long-running Angular apps?  
    Expect: debt register, prioritization with product, refactoring budget, upgrade cadence, “boy scout rule”, measurable outcomes (defects, cycle time).


 F) Project deep-dive (sprinkle into B/C)
15. Recast (Angular 9/12): data lineage dashboard—how did you model lineage and optimize rendering?  
    Expect: graph rendering approach, virtualization, incremental rendering, caching, API pagination, performance profiling evidence.
16. AOS (Angular 6): state, REST integration, and unit tests—what patterns did you use?  
    Expect: separation of concerns, services/facades, error handling, loading states, test strategy, deployment considerations.
If you say “give me answer key in table”, I’ll add a table into your Word document with columns: Question | What to listen for | Red flags | Score (1–5).
